unit.name: meter
unit.description: The meter is the length of the path travelled by light in vacuum during a time interval of 1/299 792 458 of a second (17th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1983).

unit.name: light year
unit.description: Based on 1 day = 86 400 seconds, and 1 Julian century = 36 525 days. Refer to The Astronomical Almanac for the Year 1995, U.S. Government Printing Office, Washington, DC, 1994.

unit.name: astronomical unit
unit.description: Approximately, the mean distance between the earth and the sun.

unit.name: micron
unit.description: The micron was defined as one 1 000 000th of one meter in 1879. Presently replaced with micro meter and excluded from the regal units.

unit.name: ångström
unit.description: A metric unit of length used to specify wavelengths of electromagnetic radiation.

unit.name: X unit
unit.description: A unit of measurement used to specify wavelength of X-ray.

unit.name: international nautical mile
unit.description: A unit of length used in navigation which is equivalent to the distance spanned by one second of arc in latitude. Adopted by the First International Extraordinary Hydrographic Conference, Monaco, 1929.

unit.name: rod (based on US survey foot)
unit.description: 16.5 times US survey foot (= pole or perch)

unit.name: fathom (based on US survey foot)
unit.description: 6 times US survey foot, a unit of measurement for water depth

unit.name: foot (US survey)
unit.description: From 1893 until 1959, the yard was defined as being exactly equal to 3600/3937 m, and thus the foot was defined as being exactly equal to 1200/3937 m, which was called "U.S. survey foot". 1 international foot (0.3048 m) = 0.999 998 U.S. survey foot exactly.

unit.name: kilogram
unit.description: The kilogram is the unit of mass, equal to the mass of the international prototype of the kilogram, which is an alloy column made of 90% platinum and 10% iridium, 39 millimeters in diameter and height, preserved in the suburbs of Paris (3rd CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1901).

unit.name: carat (metric)
unit.description: Used to weigh gems or noble metals. Standardized as 0.2 gram in 1907.

unit.name: atomic mass unit
unit.description: A unit to measure mass of elementary particles, atoms and molecules. 1 u is equal to 1/12 of the mass of an atom of the nuclide 12C.

unit.name: square rod (based on U.S. survey foot)
circular mil
unit.description: Area of a disk with a diameter of 1 mil.

sub.name: Power, Work Rate, Heat Flow Rate
Energy, Work, Moment of Force, Torque

unit.name: calorie (IT), kilogram (nutrition)
unit.description: The kilogram calorie (or "large calorie") is an obsolete term used for the kilocalorie, which is the calorie used to express the energy content of foods. In practice, the prefix "kilo" is usually omitted.

unit.name: calorie (th), kilogram (nutrition)
unit.description: The kilogram calorie (or "large calorie") is an obsolete term used for the kilocalorie, which is the calorie used to express the energy content of foods. In practice, the prefix "kilo" is usually omitted.

unit.name: calorie (mean), kilogram (nutrition)
unit.description: The kilogram calorie (or "large calorie") is an obsolete term used for the kilocalorie, which is the calorie used to express the energy content of foods. In practice, the prefix "kilo" is usually omitted.

unit.name: electronvolt
unit.description: The kinetic energy a electron obtains when it passes through the potential difference of 1 volt in a vacuum.

unit.name: therm(US)
unit.description: The therm (US) is legally defined in the Federal Register of July 27, 1968.

unit.name: therm(EC)
unit.description: The therm (EC) is legally defined in the Council Directive of 20 December 1979, Council of the European Communities (now the European Union, EU).

unit.name: British thermal unit (IT)
unit.description: The Fifth International Conference on the Properties of Steam (London, July 1956) defined the International Table calorie as 4.1868 J.

unit.name: British thermal unit (th)
unit.description: Based on the thermochemical calorie, cal(th), where cal(th) = 4.184 J exactly.

unit.name: knot, nautical mile per hour
unit.description: Derives from a historical fact that sailors in 17th century used to pay out a rope from ship's aft and count knots while measuring time with a sandglass to know ship's speed.

unit.name: kilogram-force per square meter
unit.description: Those who feel hard to convert pressure or stress from MKS unit system to SI, remember one kgf/cm² is about 100 kPa.

unit.name: kilogram-force second squared per meter to the fourth power

sub.name: Flow Rate, Volume Divided by Time
Mass Flow Rate, Mass Divided by Time

unit.name: kelvin
unit.description: Named for Lord William Thomson Kelvin, an English physicist. The kelvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature, is the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water (13th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1967).;Body Temp. unit.name: deg Celsius
unit.description: Named for the Swedish scientist A. Celsius in 1742. Defined as one hundredth of temperature difference between the freezing and boiling points of pure water.

unit.name: deg Réaumur
unit.description: Named for the French scientist René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur (1683-1757). The interval between the freezing and boiling temperatures of water equals to 80 °r instead of 100 °C.

unit.name: mil
unit.description: An angular unit used in artillery; equal to 1/6400 of a complete revolution.

unit.name: gon = grade
unit.description: a unit of angle equal to 0.9º

unit.name: radian
unit.description: The radian is the plane angle between two radii of a circle that cut off on the circumference an arc equal in length to the radius. 3600*180/PI

unit.name: second
unit.description: The second is the duration of 9 192 631 770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the cesium-133 atom (13th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1967).

unit.name: degree centigrade
unit.description: The centigrade temperature scale is obsolete. The degree centigrade is only approximately equal to the degree Celsius.

unit.name: deg Réaumur
unit.description: Named for the French scientist René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur (1683-1757). The interval between the freezing and boiling temperatures of water equals to 80 °r instead of 100 °C.

candela per square meter
unit.description: The candela is the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540E+12 hertz and that has a radiant intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian (16th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1979)

unit.name: volt
unit.description: Named for the Italian physicist Alessandro Volta.

unit.name: ampere
unit.description: The ampere is the constant current in two straight conductors, which have infinite length and negligible circular cross section, parallel to each other and placed 1 meter apart in vacuum, and produce a force equal to 2E-07 newton per meter of length (9th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1948).

unit.name: becquerel = 1/s
unit.description: Named for Antoine Henri Becquerel, a French Nobel prize winner (1903). Activation of nucleus disintegration. One becauerel is defined as the number of radial rays spontaneously emitted by a radioactive substance in one second, not proportional to radial energy or danger.

unit.name: sievert = J/kg
unit.description: Named for the Swedish physicist Rolf Maximilliam Sievert. Used to measure biological effect by radiation and expresses a degree of danger against human body.

unit.name: gray = J/kg
unit.description: Named for the English physicist Stephen Gray. An SI unit which expresses energy received by a substance irradiated with ionized radiation.
